A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from the fall of a lightning bolt.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And on that same line a majority of U.S. governments enacted, from 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread since the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Accordingly, in 2011 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the poll, and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to submit a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The Supreme Court of the United States in 2008 confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law.
As a result, the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with those characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Moreover, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by such clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored the reduction of the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of the Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent only 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vehemently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, the damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states passed the law requiring the presentation of an identity document with a photograph.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democrat critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that states that have passed such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say for certain whether these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
