The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume that this is Higgs, as the chances of making a mistake seem small. We will see what it is.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inevitable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because you’ll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also in it a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, grossly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And then there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories’ website Particle Adventure, which is by the way extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we won’t talk about here, and the “force particles,” by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, I should point out here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "light particle" that acts as a "messager" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "carrying force".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field and requires extremely high energies to activate it, as if it were an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the great hadron collider is a 27 km ring in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to the door of a refrigerator by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way) do not.
Now, what "can" all these investigations bring? asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to examine the differences between observations and predictions of MS.
For their part, many fervently desire to find themselves, for the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (other ups!).
But we haven’t found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research in our day-to-day life are difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say that it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories had no idea what a revolution their work would bring.
They saw the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus."
You can imagine...
In addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light pickup in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not his original intention at all, this pickup now serves as an “eye” for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That doesn’t mean, of course, that LHC activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
