But in every exchange a central authority controls and handles changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both bookkeepers, checkers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the changes of bitcoins are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to the computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file fragmentation phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
The computers "catch" the new transaction and add a number before "switching" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two on a regular basis, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and deposited bitcoins have been stolen.
“The failure used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also considers the possibility of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weight-loss actors like Wikipedia reject such payments.
Others, like the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the “giant discounts” were launched.
“They exchanged $30,000,” Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold, exults.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this coin, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as well as in the network of transactions.
Their system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to run in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They just need to provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB envisages re-evaluating the various risks, today considered high, if this currency is successful.
