A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it provisionally full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial clutter.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delusion” and continues to “betray his word” and “stomp the law.”
It is said by its supporters that this is a measure to put an end to the institutional and political crisis more quickly and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it’s also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is wreaking havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this resource has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote my text or I maintain the full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its overwhelming majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators find it funny, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies of the day was practically expressed at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the watch of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on late yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all views, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, expected that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals smear it with hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising ploy.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also heightened by the fact that the next rector of such a university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have been working on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent the civil judges are competent to rule above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Neither will prosecuting civilians in military courts, as requested by human rights associations.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy continues and, henceforth, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not in the previous constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to go on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state protested on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await the Holy Land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why Israel should be visited.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this “baptismal cell” will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of the miracles of Jesus: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the appeasement of the storm and the nets full.
In this very place, Jesus appeared to His disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here walk the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin "Painful Way").
It starts at the Fortress of Antonio, the Pretorium, where the judgment was carried out, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of crucifixion, to the Stone of Anointing and to the place of burial of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian Umbilicalum of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in AD 70.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave here notes with their desires, which will then come true.
Making a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great ordered to be built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located in the mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, can only those who dedicate themselves to climbing.
Others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
From there, bus services are offered from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly inhabited pagan gods.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
In one trip you will not be able to visit them all.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
In it are preserved the ancient Dead Sea Manuscripts or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
In his exhibition of paintings he has paintings by Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bath Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Healthy
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphins and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop by 21 degrees and the air is heated to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustain even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to take courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing muds and strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put in order their broken nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved in the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
Through it passed the famous sea route that united Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "self" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to photograph.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don’t worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to take it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently 1-3$,8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Higher City.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
Traveling on any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transshipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on the Sabbath.
From Friday night until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops close and public transport disrupts their work.
But on Sunday morning a new working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of beef and lamb dishes, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, falafel, which are ground chickpeas, fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities, there are no street dogs.
Instead, there are many well-fed cats who “walk to their liking” imposingly.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Snorkelers love crowded places and don’t reject treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, it comes out for $15 a day.
And renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, an amount that exceeds by 51% the same index as in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Will Take You to Moscow: Immigrants Save for Language
While lawmakers and human rights defenders are discussing the consequences of the compulsory examination law, there have already been whistleblowers in the country who trade in “false” certificates.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since December 1, a law comes into force, according to which each immigrant must take an exam to check his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service provision sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become compulsory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to pass the examination of the language, if not also that of Russian history and the fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
The exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law shall not apply to persons who obtained their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
Usefulness, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examining centers will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Friendship of Peoples University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to submit to the tests in all cities, currently in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on introducing the exam was supported by State Duma deputies and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, managed to often ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, this will allow to reduce the number of people who suffer from "labor slavery".
Many people talk today about defending the rights of labor immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Immigration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are with immigrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language or pass medical checks.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, throw a “paid trip” into a creepy, narrow dungeon, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they promise them one thing, but when they arrive they are defrauded, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages,” confirms the head of the Labor Immigration Directorate of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, boss!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they intend to go, but also in their own language they write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much his fault but his own misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families do not even have anything to feed the children, not to mention dressing them, shoeing them and buying them what they need for school.
Upon reaching adolescence, these guys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It’s hard, if you don’t know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the language law is concerned, rights defenders point out an important point.
Examinations will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden the passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that getting official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
Russian police officers know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be sloppy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the coming into force of the language law, it became apparent that not only immigrant registration documents can be fake.
Several "false" certificates of language proficiency have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time longer to study the basic language course.
In addition, non-Russian immigrants will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
