"For now, deceiving the brain isn't so easy"
The theme of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, has lately been commonly perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
Earlier this summer, at its annual conference, Google demonstrated a moving model and subsequently, in November, it was known that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft’s Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, it became clear that for the company’s scientists, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to the person-computer interaction, but we also try to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
Although Kinect has taken the interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We’re trying to change this, we’re working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
The computer world must be freed from our physical world, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Then we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First, to hell with those dumb virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course it cannot be considered a panacea, it is still pending to resolve the issue of privacy, since you do not always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not in looser movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of the bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this soda can?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- Usually I just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- That is, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do right now?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I believe that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do you lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, not all current technologies are good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
That is, we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on Z.
Also important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
The human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it should be mentioned that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
To me it would be very useful for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible diaphragm.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be good to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the camera location curvature and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that, from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding up a smartphone in your hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, in that is their strength (private things only you can see them), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark of the film "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There is a problem in this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile answer!
The hands feel nothing!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh burst in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the octave might well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as support for the image.
Record the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly oriented to bring tactileness to these "images in the air." For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located gives a similar sensation as one feels if someone was blowing it in the tips of the fingers, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this is also a promising direction.
- Did you try to fool the brain?
Make him think he feels what he feels he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge with which we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that it goes to an open space, almost endless. We are also working on the idea of running tapes (not like those of gyms), mobile platforms, as well as that of giant balloons.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, it still has to work for many years.
That’s what makes working with virtual reality appealing to researchers, that many things are in a state of total conception.
