As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) acts there, with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The competences are also somewhat analogous, however, as long as Germany has a federal organization, the Courts of Auditors are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data, but Germany remains a model in some respects, but it is not possible to specify exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't so, it wouldn't be of any benefit to them to collaborate with our office, would it?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post controls, a certain delay is necessary.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified.
Do you consider the passage of this law to be beneficial or rather to be a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, controlled persons were bound to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and any non-compliance with public procurement law meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only be able to create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDGs would not bother employers with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, with reference to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>warc system banned or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the government can prevent the Office’s performance which has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
He can say, “We change the law and allow it,” but he can’t say that we’ll act like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how it should be formally acted, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct, which is, in my opinion, what we are missing.
