Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of the ESA of the former Eastern Europe bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland initiated an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission in subsequent years.
However, Poland’s journey to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in the year 1925 a dresina was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the project stalls are not known either.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for starting the dresin or for braking it.
Information about this dressing is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
In 1933, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes evident that the research reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In the year 1937 appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski and the following year was published the study "Rakete - torpedo airborne and airborne bomb", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronauticze).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowiczze proposed the creation of a society that would devote itself to cosmonautics.
Projects of artificial satellites had already been launched at that time and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautics Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the RM (Meteorological Rocket) rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów desert began.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind at altitude.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland’s entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the National Committee of COSPAR two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmo after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the social work law is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated debate in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "provokes a drop" in the price of the competitor in order to get the most of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most employers, it means moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and is thus not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
All this situation fosters the total disinterest of employers to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damages they have caused in their desire to obtain profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistical data.
The scrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of their own population and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own populations without regard to social decline.
This is especially evident in changes to existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees to labour rights.
The result is a growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who can’t keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of assistance has already reached one million.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly common case: people employed with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public in connection with the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The austerity measures of virtually all the southern states of the EU lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to live with a bad wage at the limit of society, in the hope that someday private inverse capital will arrive in the country.
Is it necessary to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, as Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim to the utmost that the state should not provide capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by interfering in control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not, with its selfishness, influence the political march and, consequently, the whole state.
In this case, the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the area of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, entrust the drafting of legislation to private law firms, which are often linked to the industry.
These types of bills are later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as proclaimed in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation such as that described by Appian in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had been disintegrating for some time and administrations were engaged in force."
In exchange for bribes, illegitimately obtained favors and help to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption were self-imposed without any impediment and people went to the polls with the vote aplauded in advance"... "there were no people with character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "It began to talk about it in a serious way"... "It was necessary to think that the
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today’s society is based on disregarded preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not capable, in its essence, of understanding and claiming the benefits of the whole of society.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without any effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
Suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long run.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is, therefore, systemic.
The solution passes through concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
