In November 1979, a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah over the edge could not be allowed, since if it did, it would jeopardize the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had resulted in the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and enthusiasm against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter’s defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which garnered a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a difficult journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, to which a covert story helped an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team examining the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combinations
The plan drawn up by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood’s collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other hand, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example might be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film, moods are combined. On the one hand, we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the credit sequence are shown emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were similarly reflected in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are a bit lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: dressed men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the hallways of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of mockery, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is her third feature film, after "Goodbye little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is “wheeling” in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of true events.The introductory sequence of the embassy take is impressive for its synoptic ability that, at the same time, conveys the thrill of the baffling and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the imposter team at Tehran’s bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that a story told does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to reality: here everything doesn’t come out so elegantly (the scene of the crisis at Tehran airport, the diverting of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its tracks become madness).
Argo’s weakness is the out of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller evoking the 70s.
But if it collapses, that's gonna be hard.
