Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country has anything to do with its greed for an extremely smelly fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway’s delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how bad you prefer it.
As it darkens and gets colder, the Norwegians flock to a festival that is held here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating meal.
"You eat raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk", who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small buckets and drinking from a drink important amounts of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I try a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it’s not bad; it’s not very different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few miles by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different era, when poverty struck Norway and in which, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, obviously with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants of Sweden, the old rival and even not much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, an essential part, though quite smelly, of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A cane of beer or a sandwich cost you 10<0xE2><0x82><0xAC> ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it to be so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 incident.”
The Norwegians find it very difficult to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was able to commit such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway’s current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she passes through rakfisk trays and who, with her long blonde hair and amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, wise people.”
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like bragging, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything except a small percentage of the money coming from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn’t have during the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
“While we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a hunchback.
I'm in the snow queuing for something to eat; I've already had enough rakfisk.
Now a pine hamburger is certainly something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where guests vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A TV has connected live with a presenter who wears a little bird and is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There are laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapors of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
