Bradley Manning did not denounce ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of Bradley Manning abuse during his imprisonment
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the grounds that Manning’s imprisonment was severe.
The military soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that soldier Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while under military detention.
During the prosecution’s interrogation of Manning in a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein said the records of the weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing in response to the defense’s request that the case be dismissed as his imprisonment had been harsh and had already been punishable enough, came a day after Manning testified that he had thought of committing suicide while detained.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
On Friday’s sighting, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out following Manning’s visits during his arrest at the military prison of Quantico, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the locksmiths as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those issues and indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about the problems) but that doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the January 2011 meeting with a board in charge of examining the suicide intentions he had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the senior staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marines' base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, that cage,” Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that once he was transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the day in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a few cheekbones, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the locksmiths could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s attorney filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of lockers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the bailiff's order that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used his underwear elastics or buckles to self-harm, but he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, underwear and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
Her lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she experienced during her imprisonment and drastically reduce her sentence in case she is convicted at the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to minor crimes and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules of enforcement to any detainees who are in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from the national defense, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
Many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times
Navarrette says Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely descended the esplanade and arrived at the immigration processing zone and was already totally confused.
Some signs indicated the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where to go.
Growing up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" all my life.
This is ethnic tachygraphy, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians."
Later I decided to call myself "Mexico-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather’s homeland, tachygraphing or screenplays were not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Good enough to handle during an interview in this language.
But I don’t have the vocabulary level of a native and I can’t get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when President-elect of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, was: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also looking forward to talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at this time a Mexican is as likely to stay in Mexico as he is to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trade bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Probably most Americans never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think of centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them of it are everywhere.
So, by the time a U.S. official says anything that brings the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma stand up for war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a whole challenge is with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about resentment?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it is not.
The only reason that there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of study, coming from a poor people, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not in Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, not the Mexican dream.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the ruling class elite do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us above the shoulder as if we were of a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And now we would not find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally came to the United States when I was a girl, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the first know more firmly who they are and the second this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they are not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican band The North Tigers, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, they see us as Americans.
In the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate things, as I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised “ambassadors” of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much resentment.
And, with wage inequality, galloping corruption and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure it’s a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, friends.
That's fair.
If some Mexicans are still unprepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated much less time ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexicans" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of the useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel’s metropolis, and the holy city.
But, even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their ancient conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything shattered whether you like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been trapped in the regional upheaval.
Perhaps this will make your struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their lethal dead-end situation could unravel.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the agreed ceasefire is maintained on November 21, this week’s clashes have reinforced the falcons on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on Gaza’s 1.7 million people in one of the world’s most miserable and populous corners, Israel has failed to put an end to Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals to Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a renaissance regional power that had previously been Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and most dynamic states.
Hamas exultant members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah militia party dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, to reach Jordan, where Hamas’ allies are threatening the king.
