Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is Hamas’s cousin and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas emerges as a protagonist to whom one cannot exclude, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel’s Iron Dome missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep quieter... for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the United States is firmer than ever; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
