The world’s toughest trade: Kawah Ijen’s human mules
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano play life and health loading 70 kilograms of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is a hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, you have to go down every day to the bottom of your crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from Earth’s bowels solidifies when it comes into contact with air.
After plucking large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that he loads on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle’s pace, keeping their balance and gently measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any transplant could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who got away with the risks of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photographed them as circus monkeys and, tiredly loading the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better to say, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilogram of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to manufacture matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual it is to load 70 kilos, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries out three porters daily.
It takes three hours in each and it ends up grinding, but they allow you to collect 138.000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhumane effort, it is three times what I would win in the field.
“The miners’ newspaper is very high here, where the coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” clarifies the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the tajo was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have translated her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has three playing skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pass bills despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price you have to pay to get your dream done.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man might be a hotel guide, waiter or receptionist, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden cabin with other carriers, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to flow at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends to the crater, glowing with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its small profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs, nor does it supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at the same time the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera charge that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old gifted carrier who has been in the Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilograms, he says he will endure working "everything he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and slaps the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and knees have been hurt.
By swinging the basket over his back, Unainik can only load 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his companions pluck 15 tons of sulfur into the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away on a goat road between the weeds.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but perpetual misery from generation to generation is one of the toughest jobs in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
