1.2 Children
The one who does not take it so lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech state city in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, according to its national population division, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replacement rate – was in 1976.
So why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policies at the National Population Division, says it is due to “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
