Start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew that he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the next couple of months: the cataclysmic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal precipice that some have called “debt-magedon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If one analyzes what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that evil is good for those of apocalyptic mindset.
And he’s not the only professor offering courses on the “end of the world” this semester, in theory the latest in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyzed why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month the students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
“I have tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
At Pennsylvania State University’s main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only “The End of the World.”
“We don’t add ‘2012’ to always have the option of teaching the course again, in case the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the same night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
"It saturated in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received email messages for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of the career in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a class that could teach that,” he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a professor — said they believed the December 21 expiration date.
“Our first project dealt with Maya prophecy and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple and West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, in which people react to the changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom of these speculations.
“Otherwise, people don’t think about this,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any course about the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, implying an exception from a superior authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21st, “people will start immediately thinking about the next date” or philosophizing that December 21st is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end of the world" parties.
“Maybe I’ll call some friends and we’ll laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
